The course provides an overview of the ideas of Europe's major political philosophers.  A selection of the following authors will be discussed: Socrates, Platon, Aristotle, Machiavelli, Hobbes, Locke, Montesquieu, Rousseau, Kant, Wollstonecraft, Burke, Herder, Hegel, Mill, Marx.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The aims of the course are to: - provide basic knowledge of the main ideas of the most important European political philosophers from Socrates to Marx; - teach students to analyse texts of political theory, specifying the main problem that the author is tackling, reconstructing the argument and assessing it critically; - teach students to analyse the authors` and their texts' relationship to historical context; - to raise students' awareness of the historical origins and complex evolution of our current central political concepts; - teach students to discuss problems in political theory and to justify their normative views on politics.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student who has fulfilled the course successfully: 1) has an overview of the main ideas of the most important European political philosophers; 2) is able to analyse texts of political theory, specifying the main aims and solutions of the author; 3) is able to relate the key ideas of the texts discussed to the historical context; 4) can specify the most important interpretations of the key concepts of political philosophy, is able to compare and analyse their meaning in different contexts; 5) is able to discuss problems in political theory and to give a justification of their own normative views on politics.
